# Special Rules - Suspicious Activity Monitoring -------------------------------
# NOTE: These rules are carefully curated to avoid noise from normal operations

## Network Tools (Potential Attack Tools)
### Netcat/nc - Often used for reverse shells and port scanning
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/bin/nc -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k suspicious_network
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/bin/netcat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k suspicious_network

### Base64 encoding - Often used to obfuscate payloads (monitor only by regular users)
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/bin/base64 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k suspicious_encoding
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/bin/base32 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k suspicious_encoding

## Firewall Configuration Changes (Critical Security)
### NFT (nftables) - Monitor all firewall changes
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/sbin/nft -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k firewall_changes

## Network Reconnaissance (Optional - may be legitimate troubleshooting)
### Traceroute - Network mapping
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/sbin/traceroute -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k network_recon

## Monitor dbus-send usage which was exploited in CVE-2021-3560
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/bin/dbus-send -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k dbus_manipulation

## Shell Profile Modifications (Persistence Mechanism)
### Attackers often modify these files to maintain persistence
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S openat2,openat,open -F dir=/etc/profile.d/ -F perm=wa -k shell_profiles
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S openat2,openat,open -F path=/etc/profile -F perm=wa -k shell_profiles
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S openat2,openat,open -F path=/etc/shells -F perm=wa -k shell_profiles
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S openat2,openat,open -F path=/etc/bash.bashrc -F perm=wa -k shell_profiles

## Code Injection Detection (Ptrace)
### Detect attempts to inject code, data, or modify registers via ptrace
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F a0=0x4 -k code_injection
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F a0=0x5 -k data_injection
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F a0=0x6 -k register_injection
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F a0=0x10 -k ptrace_attach
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F a0=0x4200 -k ptrace_seize

### General ptrace monitoring (may be noisy if debugging tools are used)
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S ptrace -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k tracing

## Anonymous File Creation (Fileless Execution)
### memfd_create allows running executables from memory without touching disk
### Combined with fexecve, this enables stealthy malware execution
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S memfd_create -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k anonymous_file_creation
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execveat -F a0!=-100 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -k fd_execution

## Privilege Abuse Detection (Admin accessing sensitive Wazuh data)
### Monitor when an authenticated admin reads agent keys or API credentials
### This is the crown jewel of a Wazuh deployment
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S openat2,openat,open -F path=/var/ossec/etc/client.keys -F uid=0 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F success=1 -k admin_wazuh_key_access

# DELIBERATELY NOT MONITORED (to avoid excessive noise):
# - Wazuh queue/var/stats/logs writes by uid 101 (wazuh): Normal operations
# - Wazuh Indexer data directory by uid 988 (wazuh-indexer): Constant I/O
# - Socket creation: Would generate thousands of events per minute
# - General bash execution: Would flood logs with every command
# - wget/curl: Used by Wazuh for CDB list updates and vulnerability detection
# - Agent communication on ports 1514/1515: Core Wazuh functionality

# Make the audit configuration immutable (requires reboot to modify)
# WARNING: Once this is enabled, you cannot modify audit rules without rebooting
# Comment out during testing, enable for production
-e 2
